############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0); $flour=NumberWithUnits("13/24",'cup'); $ev=$flour->cmp(correct_ans_latex_string => "\frac{13}{24}\text{ cup}");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML A chef had [`\frac{2}{3}`] cups of flour and needed to use [`\frac{1}{8}`] cup to thicken a sauce. How much flour is left? [_]{$ev}{15}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION We need to compute [`\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8}\text{.}`] The denominators are [`3`] and [`8\text{.}`] One common denominator is [`24\text{,}`] so we move to rewrite each fraction using [`24`] as the denominator:
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} \frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8}\amp=\frac{2\cdot8}{3\cdot8} - \frac{1\cdot3}{8\cdot3}\\ \amp=\frac{16}{24}-\frac{3}{24}\\ \amp=\frac{13}{24} \end{aligned} ```]
The numerical result is [`\frac{13}{24}\text{,}`] but a pure number does not answer this question. The amount of flour remaining is [`\frac{13}{24}`] _cups_.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
